<DOC><DOCNO> AP891117-0279 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-17-89 0105EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-JunkBonds-Mergers     11-17 0182</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Junk Bonds-Mergers,0188</SECOND><HEAD>Junk Bond Sales For Mergers Dropped By More Than Half, Magazine Says</HEAD><DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The percentage of mergers funded by junkbonds dropped by more than half in the first nine months of theyear, Mergers andamp; Acquisitions magazine said Thursday.   Junk bonds, which many buyers have viewed with caution in recentmonths, were used to finance only 8.5 percent of the $133.3 billionworth of mergers in the first three quarters of the year, saidMartin Sikora, editor of Mergers andamp; Acquisitions, which says it hasfollowed 39,000 deals since 1979.   In the first nine months of last year, junk bonds were sold toraise 19.5 percent of the $132.9 billion worth of deals, thePhiladelphia-based magazine said.   More than $11.3 billion worth of junk bonds were sold as part ofmergers in the first nine months of 1989, while nearly $25.9billion were sold to finance acquisitions in the same period lastyear.   Owners of junk, or low-grade, bonds accept a higher risk ofdefault in exchange for the high yields offered by the securities.</TEXT></DOC>